You want this final setup:

üéØ Goal
	‚Ä¢	Be able to run simply:

.\liquibase.bat update

	‚Ä¢	Without specifying:
	‚Ä¢	--changelog-file
	‚Ä¢	--search-path
	‚Ä¢	--url
	‚Ä¢	--username
	‚Ä¢	--password
	‚Ä¢	And also be able to run Liquibase directly from your Java project using the same config.

This is 100% possible using only liquibase.properties.
No environment variables needed.
No PowerShell syntax issues.
No broken arguments.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ 1. Create a liquibase.properties file

Create this file:

C:\Users\RHABACHI\Downloads\liquibase-4.33.0\liquibase.properties

Or (better):

C:\Users\RHABACHI\IdeaProjects\bankinfo\liquibase\liquibase.properties

Put this inside:

searchPath=C:/Users/RHABACHI/IdeaProjects/bankinfo/liquibase
changelogFile=changelogMaster.yaml

url=jdbc:mariadb://localhost:3306/external_bank_data
username=root
password=root

# optional: log level
logLevel=info

‚ö†Ô∏è IMPORTANT:
Liquibase 4.20+ uses camelCase, not kebab-case nor snake_case:

‚ùå --changelog-file
‚úîÔ∏è changelogFile=

‚ùå --search-path
‚úîÔ∏è searchPath=

Without correct casing, it fails.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ 2. Run Liquibase with no arguments

Go to your Liquibase folder:

cd C:\Users\RHABACHI\Downloads\liquibase-4.33.0

Then run:

.\liquibase.bat update

üéâ It will automatically:
	‚Ä¢	load liquibase.properties
	‚Ä¢	know your changelog file
	‚Ä¢	know your search path
	‚Ä¢	know your DB credentials
	‚Ä¢	execute without arguments

‚∏ª

‚ùó Why your command failed earlier

You saw this:

Error parsing command line: Invalid argument '--changelog-file': missing required argument.

Because:
	‚Ä¢	The argument is now deprecated
	‚Ä¢	It must be:
	‚Ä¢	--changelog-file=<value>
	‚Ä¢	Or better: changelogFile=... in liquibase.properties

But using liquibase.properties removes all these issues.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ 3. Running Liquibase from your Java Spring project

Spring Boot will automatically detect your liquibase.properties IF it is placed in:

src/main/resources/liquibase.properties

Or you can point Spring to it via:

spring:
  liquibase:
    config: classpath:liquibase.properties

Then you can run in your Java code:

Liquibase liquibase = new Liquibase();
liquibase.update();

Or even better:
Let Spring Boot run it automatically at startup.

‚∏ª

üî• BONUS (Optional): Set system environment variables

If you really want environment variables, Liquibase expects:

setx LIQUIBASE_COMMAND_CHANGELOG_FILE "changelogMaster.yaml"
setx LIQUIBASE_SEARCH_PATH "C:\Users\RHABACHI\IdeaProjects\bankinfo\liquibase"

Then run a new PowerShell window (setx requires restart), then:

.\liquibase.bat update

But truly:
The recommended and clean solution is liquibase.properties.

